{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"da74de2f-dae2-41b8-b891-d9f8b2d8fff9","content":"In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class and work the same way. However, the recommended modern approach is to use **Window lifecycle events**:\n\n**Option 1 — Override in a custom `Window`:**\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* replaces OnStart */ }\n    protected override void OnDeactivated(){ /* replaces OnSleep */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* replaces OnResume */ }\n}\n```\nThen in your `App.xaml.cs`:\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow { Page = new AppShell() };\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Platform-specific hooks in `MauiProgram.cs`:**\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(a => a.OnStop(activity => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios.DidEnterBackground(app => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Your existing overrides will still compile and run. For finer control, move to the `Window`-level events (`OnCreated`, `OnResumed`, `OnDeactivated`, `OnStopped`, `OnDestroying`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"436c79f7-efbe-4b41-8329-850fd4fdd6b1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI, specifically about the Application lifecycle methods (OnStart, OnSleep, OnResume). This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the approach changed. You use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — but the recommended approach is to use the cross-platform lifecycle events via `CreateWindow` or the platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`.\n\n\nThe good news is MAUI hasn't removed those methods from the `Application` class, so your existing code might still work. However, the modern way forward is leveraging the `Window` lifecycle events — you can override `CreateWindow` and hook into events like `Created`, `Resumed`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, and `Destroying`, or use the lifecycle configuration in your `MauiProgram` setup.","outputTokens":751,"requestId":"1017:92DE6:15BBA1F:18563C1:69FD34A1"},"id":"aee89798-dde1-4019-bfb3-f5f43107bfa5","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:56:16.149Z","parentId":"c731c9b8-dc0a-4717-8756-dad3e4351392"}
